      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Battle of Buffalo</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Karl Schwartz letter on New York State Senate campaign debate says man of honor would have stepped in and urged Hillary Clinton not to dignify Tim Russert's vicious attack on her defense of her husband's fidelity; notes that Rick Lazio seized opportunity to further humiliate Mrs Clinton (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>A man of honor would have stepped in and urged Hillary Rodham Clinton not to dignify Tim Russert's vicious attack on her defense of her husband's fidelity. Instead, Representative Rick A. Lazio seized the opportunity to further humiliate Mrs. Clinton.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>A man of honor would have stepped in and urged Hillary Rodham Clinton not to dignify Tim Russert's vicious attack on her defense of her husband's fidelity. Instead, Representative Rick A. Lazio seized the opportunity to further humiliate Mrs. Clinton.</p>
        <p>Politics and honor need not be mutually exclusive. We learn much about a man who comes to the defense of a political opponent who is unfairly victimized. We also learn much about a man who does not.</p>
        <p>KARL SCHWARTZ  Philadelphia, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
